=1> Freeport has been taken over by the Freeport Militia and the paladins are now isolated in a new area known as Marr. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(phuk-da-molishuh!)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Qeynos has defeated the rogues and now has a new city. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(i dun give a phuk)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The moon of the Vah Shir and the home of the Iksar are now gone, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(Woohoo! They were so ghay)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> but the Iksar still remain. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(this is sm00th)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Vah Shir no longer roam the lands, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(ahh hahaha. Yeah, they were 'really' useful in EQ as we can see here. *snicker, chuckle*)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> but Kerrans have risen in their absence. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(great, only to be replaced by another group of pussies. *eyeroll*)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <br>
A player will not assign his or her character stats upon creation. They will choose their race, sex, and appearance.<br>
Classes and stat assigments will occur later in the game. At level 6 (which is rumored to take 30 minutes to attain), a player picks a base class: fighter, priest, mage, rogue or tradesman. At level 15 you may specialize further. Your final specialization will occur at level 30, which will determine your class for the rest of that character's life.<br>
<br>
The level cap is 100, which may be extended in expansions. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(we have 100 levels and only get to specialize at lvls 6, 15 and 30?! wtf? like they couldnt put a few more different classes/ name variations in there just to keep a long ass 70 level run interesting. fuckers...)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>((and dont even give me that, &quot;They'll fix it later&quot; bullshit either. Tell that to everyone who ever owned a Manastone, for example. Yeah, they fixed that. lol)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Leveling will also be faster than it currently is in EverQuest. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(ok...good for melee's and the like I guess)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
It is expected that all of the current EverQuest races will make it into EverQuest II except for the Vah Shir, who will be replaced by the Kerra. (That makes the race line-up the following: Barbarian, Dark Elf, Dwarf, Erudite, Gnome, Half Elf, Halfling, High Elf, Human, Iksar, Kerran, Ogre, Troll, Wood Elf.) <br>
<br>
EverQuest II will have a branching class structure that a player defines as he advances through the game. The Tradesman class will provide options for advancement if a player wishes to play the game without confrontation. <br>
<br>
There are 5 base classes: Fighter, Priest, Mage, Rogue, and Tradesman. At level 15, a player may further specialize his class At level 30, a player determines the final specialization for the rest of the character's life. EXAMPLE: If a player chooses the Fighter base class at level 6, he may choose between Warrior, Crusader, or Brawler at level 15. At level 30, if he chose Crusader at level 15, he can become a Paladin, Shadowknight or Ranger. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(That's pretty tight that they're returning back to some of the O.G. names as the final name in class progression/ specialization.)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
There will be 3 main skills that are used to improve your character: <br>
<br>
Knowledge: Affects the level of items you can equip<br>
Technique: Determines how well you can use weapons or items<br>
Arts: Handles basic functions such as foraging and kicking (ok...so....where will our extra mana, hp, stamina, etc...come from? Guess I missed that... Seems semi-gay to nerf stats down to an entire skill system though. Think of what D&amp;D or Palladium would be like with just 3 skills. &quot;brrrt!&quot;)<br>
<br>
Players will now be able to purchase land and housing. The structure that a player builds on his land is upgradable. As towns form, guard towers and NPCs will spawn to protect the towns. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(can I get Sargeant Slaughter, Gaurd Vallon and Colin protectin my @#%$? LOL!)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Well, not as it is today. The Knowledge skill deals with your ability to use items. <br>
<br>
Basically, an item that requires a Knowledge skill of 75 can be used by, say, a level 10. However, the item will have a significant reduction in effectiveness. <br>
<br>
Also, EQII will have 'transient' items. This means that items can break. This level 10 player will not have the Knowledge skill of 75 required to wield the weapon effectively, and he will have a significantly increased chance to break the item with use. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(boo-phuking-hoo. no more twinking. Now, instead of us farming @#%$ when lowbies are beggin for the camp/ item, we actually have to go find something else to do *cheers*)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
While the death system is not yet fully fleshed out, there will still be a fairly heavy penalty for dying in EverQuest 2. Corpse recovery will no longer occupy hours of your time: your corpse will remain for a while to provide for a resurrection, but you will spawn at your bind point with everything except an item or two. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(hopefully we can specify what items we want to lose. ie: carrying around junk item to leave on corpse for a ressurection. if not, then I still see hours of CR's = ghay)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
When you die, you incur an Experience Debt: This means that you will have to acquire more experience to obtain the next level, but you don't actually lose experience so you won't ever lose that hard-earned level. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(I never liked &quot;Exp-Skates&quot; anyways) ((don't be stealing my quote now phukerz. lol))</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
Bindpoints will be scattered about the world in relative abundance. You will never be more than 5 minutes away from one. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>(roxorz!)</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
